text:
my great aunt had a love spice on her stove. the kitchen was always spotless, she took her christmas tree down on december 26th, and the house smelled of flour, cookies and on sundays a roast. 
but the love spice was always on the top of the range. 
the secret ingredient was always love

her house was the perfect munchie house with sugar cookies and bars and booze that had only been watered down by all the kids. 
some nights the kids would stay up back from a party and she‚Äôd come out with noxema on her face and curlers in the hair, calling us monkeys and yell to go to bed

and the secret ingredient was always love. 
it could be a tense week this week with the stars and post eclipse energy- 
i hope you experience and express the secret ingredient to who deserves it and who doesn‚Äôt, most of all yourself. 
and when you need a little extra dose of acceptance or the sense that all will be well, come hang out here for a while üòâüíïüíóüíö

text:
in recent years there have been increasing efforts made to bring awareness to predatory behaviors among men and women. this is a great step in the right direction. women are finding their voices, and are uniting to help others who haven‚Äôt yet found theirs. we are starting to hold predators accountable for their actions. 
although i am hopeful to see us moving towards holding predators accountable for their horrendous actions, i do believe that the problem doesn‚Äôt end there. as a therapist, i am trained to view things from all angles in efforts to resolve issues from the root up, which decreases the chance of them reoccurring. if we only look at one part of a problem, we take the chance of the larger issue reoccurring, but with different predators and different victims. a person can not become a leader or be in a position of power, if there isn‚Äôt a supportive following. and a predator isn‚Äôt powerful enough to continue predatory behaviors unless there are people who help reinforce these behaviors. predators with power are the most dangerous ones, they get a pass and continue to gain support from their following. if predators were no longer supported (concerts, sales, votes, shows, streams, etc.), they‚Äôd lose power, and powerless predators aren‚Äôt usually able to continue predatory behaviors without legal consequences. we as a society need to look at the entire picture when a traumatic series of events occur- we must ask questions like; who all is responsible? who is paying the legal fees? who is buying tickets? who is attending rallies?.
in order to prevent these things from happening in the future we must also think of the lessons we must learn, or what lessons we must teach our sons and daughters. we must recognize that the power in one person is only as big as what we make it. the moment we take back our support, we take back their power. predatory behaviors, as many other issues, are a result of an entire system. when we dismantle the system, we discontinue the problem. ‚Ä¢

thanks for being so patient everyone!
i hope you enjoy the rest of the new year!

text:
my son was on skis two weeks after his first birthday. we‚Äôve been snowboarding üèÇ since he was about four. he would start out good and once he picked up speed he would always stop and fall.

after overcoming my own fears in a elite transformational coaching group i recognized his fear and knew it well.

it was the same fear that i manifested in my own coaching business. i was afraid of the time and responsibilities that would follow if i were to become successful in my coaching business. i allowed this fear to hold me back and allow me to play safe. 
the same fear my son had about going fast down the hill. so i sat down with him and explained how speed helps you get moving down that hill and when you are moving too fast you pivot to the side and slow down a bit but you keep moving forward. 
he overcame his fear and killed it on the hill! you see me at one point in the end in red boarding pants in front of my son. i am so proud of him. he may have become scared at times but he kept going and moving forward. he didn‚Äôt stop and he even enjoyed himself!

these same fears i had in my business were given up for courage and commitment to the impact i want to make for women in my business. 
if you‚Äôre like me and work full time and want to start or grow your own online business, don‚Äôt let fear of time and responsibility stand in your way. i have so much i can teach you about processes and time management as well as transitioning from the mindset of employee to entrepreneur. reach out or join the lifestyle coaching academy community i‚Äôve created. i‚Äôm here to help you succeed.
name: Solutions 4 Busy Entrepreneurs

text:
i heard about r. kelly's treatment of young, black women a few years back and never looked at him the same again. i grew up playing his music. he was a favorite of mine. but after hearing accusations against him i couldn't listen to his music anymore without a sick feeling in my stomach. even if i wasn't 1 out of 4, i would still know that this is wrong. he is wrong. 
if these young ladies were white, he would have been stopped. a long ass time ago he would have been stopped. we (talking to you fellow white people) cannot keep sitting by and allowing these things to happen to women of color. 
we need to start having each others backs. believing in each other. men need to start calling out other men for their bullshit. 
i don't have answers to the worlds problems. but i know its time for change. 
#muterkelly
#metoo

text:
#celebrationoverresolution - in 2018 i was able to recognize that there are issues that i am still struggling with; things i thought i was ‚Äòover‚Äô, but am definitely not.  the #metoo movement really hit home for me, and shook a lot of feelings loose.  then dr. blasey ford took the stand against brett kavanaugh, and i was shocked, and frankly alarmed, by the amount of anger and depression i felt.  it had been years since my own sexual assaults, but watching her under oath, scrolling through blogs and comment sections on the topic, i realized that i needed help.  i talked to my dad for the first time about what i‚Äôd experienced, and i accepted his offer to help me find a therapist to finally process properly.  and that‚Äôs something worth celebrating!  it‚Äôs not a big, obvious feat, but too often it‚Äôs easier to ignore our feelings, and deny that we need help.  it will definitely be a painful journey, but i‚Äôm proud to have recognized such steps need to be taken. 
what did you do in 2018 that deserves some celebration, amongst all of the new years resolutions?  if you post about it, tag me, and use the hashtag #celebrationoverresolution, you could win $200 in beautiful gifts from some of my fave self-loving shops!  check 4 posts back for all the details üíï

text:
lauren chose ‚Äùthe lone ranger and tanto fist fight in heaven‚Äù as one of her #favepageturners this for 2 reasons: ‚Äú1) it is the 20th anniversary edition of this book and it made me realize how long i've been a fan of alexie. i first started reading him in 1994 (i'm guessing) back when he was only a poet and his novel was in the works. poetry is very hit or miss for me and his slammed into my heart and brain. his tragic humor came through and i was hooked. when this book came out i told everyone i have a favourite living author now! i've heard him speak 3x and met him once.¬†
2) in 2018 as part of the #metoo movement it came out that he had been a jerk and was using his status as an author over women trying to get published. it made me so angry that i didn't read the autobiography i got for christmas in 2017. however now a year has passed and i saw tonto on the shelf and it brought back all of the good memories about alexie and his books. i'm ok now recommending his books again. this one particularly stands the test of time and the gallows humor is the main element. oh and the movie is good too!‚Äù

text: i grew up #hiphop and in the 80s-early 90s there was so much #messagemusic. hip-hop wasn‚Äôt afraid to be #political or take a stand so when #rodneyking was assaulted, we bumped #fthepolice hard. while we know all police aren‚Äôt corrupt it was a powerful message in the face of blatant #policebrutality. i might not have declared it fully before but i‚Äôm doing it now. i admit that months ago i listened to #iadmitit and almost took the bait. for a brief moment of melody and ‚Äúexpose‚Äù i started wondering if there was any merit...wondering if #rkelly was somehow exploited. a master of #deflection; #manipulation i know something about. it was a tirade of a #sociopath. #period. im saddened that he was abused as a child but it‚Äôs not a pass or license (many of us have had various challenges). he strategized and orchestrated his perversion (with a lot of help too). as i revisit my own #domesticabuse and #sexualexplotation...sadly, i can relate to the women of #survivingrkelly. i was a minor too when i was ‚Äúgroomed‚Äù...‚Äùeducated‚Äù...‚Äùtrained.‚Äù today, i say...#no! #timesup #metoo #endrapeculture #lifetime #muterkelly #melodyfoxmedia

text: after watching the surviving r.kelly docuseries, i think this is an important topic to touch on now more than ever. obviously, through schooling and my typical line of work, i get it and understand the entire domestic violence process. unfortunately, not many people do though. these kinds of relationships can happen in a number of ways. abuse/dv can be mental, physical, emotion, financial, etc. abuse/dv is all about having power and control over another. people dismiss abuse and domestic violence because they are taught to just as the abuser was taught to abuse or learned to become the way they are as a way to take control of a previous situation or feeling they never wanted again. the #metoo movement brought a lot of things to light for me. i wasn‚Äôt taught all the different kinds of abuse growing up and i honestly don‚Äôt think most people have. this is why i believe this subject is very important. i also believe it is important for men to understand that they can be abused and this applies to them as well. i could honestly discuss this topic all day, but the main reason for this post is to help others become aware of some different forms of abuse and its affects on their children if they have any. this power and control wheel is not discussed or even shown often enough so i am here to hopefully make a difference for someone. whether you are the abuser or the abused, i hope you really take a look at this and see how your actions are affecting the people around you. now is not the time to play the blame game. it‚Äôs time to make a change. #stopdomesticviolence #stopabuse #metoo #children #parents #relationships #sos #help #power #control #powerandcontrol
name: J.Carr
tweet_full: after watching the surviving r.kelly docuseries, i think this is an important topic to touch on now more than ever. obviously, through schooling and my typical line of work, i get it and understand the entire domestic violence process. unfortunately, not many people do though. these kinds of relationships can happen in a number of ways. abuse/dv can be mental, physical, emotion, ficial, etc. abuse/dv is all about having power and control over another. people dismiss abuse and domestic violence because they are taught to just as the abuser was taught to abuse or learned to become the way they are as a way to take control of a previous situation or feeling they never wanted again. the #metoo movement brought a lot of things to light for me. i wasn‚Äôt taught all the different kinds of abuse growing up and i honestly don‚Äôt think most people have. this is why i believe this subject is very important. i also believe it is important for men to understand that they can be abused and this applies to them as well. i could honestly discuss this topic all day, but the main reason for this post is to help others become aware of some different forms of abuse and its affects on their children if they have any. this power and control wheel is not discussed or even shown often enough so i am here to hopefully make a difference for someone. whether you are the abuser or the abused, i hope you really take a look at this and see how your actions are affecting the people around you. now is not the time to play the blame game. it‚Äôs time to make a change. #stopdomesticviolence #stopabuse #metoo #children #parents #relationships #sos #help #power #control #powerandcontrol

text:
3am night feed and i‚Äôm cruising the intarwebz while feeding my little squish. seeing all those pregnant bellies of other ttc / pregnancy pages i follow fills my heart with a sense of deep nostalgia already. i‚Äôm so glad i savored my pregnancy in the way i did, because i already miss it desperately. it was harder this time than the last time - the fatigue was worse, and it was impossible to care for my toddler with that belly - but my god do i miss the magic and anticipation of it all, already ‚ù§Ô∏è
‚Ä¢
as for sander, he nursed from 1:30pm until 7:17pm yesterday üôÄ i‚Äôd call it cluster-feeding but isn‚Äôt cluster-feeding supposed to be temporary? this child has been nursing for 6-hour stretches literally since the moment he was born - he was latched straight from birth (at noon) till dinner time that day!
‚Ä¢
i‚Äôm hoping these long sessions increase my milk supply. sander has finally stopped losing weight but he‚Äôs still 8.4% down from birth weight and his doctors are watching us like a hawk :/ i went in yesterday for a check up and now need to return today, and possibly tomorrow and the next day to see that his weight continues to rise.
‚Ä¢
i‚Äôll also get a copy of my birth journal tomorrow and i‚Äôll be able to record my birth story üòç the way it went down was totally unexpected and even the midwife i saw yesterday said to me, ‚Äúi read your file and i‚Äôm still trying to figure out what happened there... ü§î‚Äù üòÇüòÇ #metoo!
‚Ä¢

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

reuters

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied. 
in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
surviving r. kelly' documentary features victims of the singer as they share harrowing details of sex abuse 
for over 20 years, r. kelly has been accused by multiple women of sexual misconduct and abuse but he has so far denied all the allegations.

this week, a documentary produced by lifetime is exploring the allegations brought against robert kelly.

multiple alleged victims of the singer, including his ex-wife andrea kelly all featured in the documentary and they spoke about their ordeal.

as expected, a lot of tears were shed as the women recounted the alleged abuse - sexual, mental, emotional, and physical - which they suffered in the hands of r. kelly. 
the documentary, made up of six parts, includes commentary from r. kelly‚Äôs critics, including the founder of the #metoo movement, tarana burke, and the singer john legend.

the docu-series has gained attention and is being widely debated on social media, with a lot of people saying the singer has escaped the consequences of his actions for far too long. there were also those who came to the defence of the singer.

#newsupdate 
#foreignnews 
#follow4followback 
#naija

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text_retweet:
#repost @indiaarie with @get_repost
„Éª„Éª„Éª
take a moment to read my thoughts: i boycotted r. kelleys music in 2002 when i saw the video ~ i know it was him. clearly.  i wasn‚Äôt comfortable talking about it because the world i lived in .... everyone thought it was a joke, and they made me feel ike i was too earnest. i saw the bbc documentary, i read the buzz feed and new yorker articles ... as a #survivor and a black woman in the music industry, i just broke down sobbing when i saw the video. i sobbed, because it was a graphic illustration, that i lived in a world that didnt value people like me. and i had to learn to take care of myself in the face of a society and industry that doesn‚Äôt love me. i learned that i had to wear the crown of my ancestors and hold my own head up. and its been hard. but i do it because i believe in my mission ~ i don‚Äôt need to sing about the fight , my mission is to administer to the people in the fight. humanity makes me sad all the time ~ the things were going thru ... but also today, i‚Äôm hopeful, that we as a group are now #muterkelly ~ but, i wont be satisfied until every abused person knows, that ‚Äúeveryone of us is worthy‚Äù and when ever someone treats us as less, that is thier mistake, ... and while the wound is not our doing, it is our responsibility ~ we have to heal ourselves.  that healing can take on so much more momentum, when the world around us is healing too.... so i feel good today knowing that we as a collective are waking up even more, to the ways that the world / the music industry / the society / the culture ~ harm our women and girls.  and! i feel good today knowing that these growing pains are about growth. we are all! worthy and significant and we matter! because we exist!  may we keep waking up to that fact. it is a fact! everyone of us is #worthy #worthy #worthy #worthy #worthy #worthy #survivingrkelly #iamlight #muterkelly #survivingrkelly #rkelly #blackgirlsmatter #metoo

text_retweet: reposted from @indiaarie -  take a moment to read my thoughts: i boycotted r. kelleys music in 2002 when i saw the video ~ i know it was him. clearly.  i wasn‚Äôt comfortable talking about it because the world i lived in .... everyone thought it was a joke, and they made me feel ike i was too earnest. i saw the bbc documentary, i read the buzz feed and new yorker articles ... as a #survivor and a black woman in the music industry, i just broke down sobbing when i saw the video. i sobbed, because it was a graphic illustration, that i lived in a world that didnt value people like me. and i had to learn to take care of myself in the face of a society and industry that doesn‚Äôt love me. i learned that i had to wear the crown of my ancestors and hold my own head up. and its been hard. but i do it because i believe in my mission ~ i don‚Äôt need to sing about the fight , my mission is to administer to the people in the fight. humanity makes me sad all the time ~ the things were going thru ... but also today, i‚Äôm hopeful, that we as a group are now #muterkelly ~ but, i wont be satisfied until every abused person knows, that ‚Äúeveryone of us is worthy‚Äù and when ever someone treats us as less, that is thier mistake, ... and while the wound is not our doing, it is our responsibility ~ we have to heal ourselves.  that healing can take on so much more momentum, when the world around us is healing too.... so i feel good today knowing that we as a collective are waking up even more, to the ways that the world / the music industry / the society / the culture ~ harm our women and girls.  and! i feel good today knowing that these growing pains are about growth. we are all! worthy and significant and we matter! because we exist!  may we keep waking up to that fact. it is a fact! everyone of us is #worthy #worthy #worthy #worthy #worthy #worthy #survivingrkelly #iamlight #muterkelly #survivingrkelly #rkelly #blackgirlsmatter #metoo - #regrann

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
1 in 5 female children are sexually abused in the us. the us is one of the few countries that even bothers to get the statistics on this issue. research also shows that this is so underreported so numbers are higher. but i didn‚Äôt need research to confirm that, especially since i am yet to meet any woman who when the issue of sexual abuse came up was not abused, or did not know at least one person close to her that was sexually abused. .
.
when i became a health care professional, i saw another side of this evil - the effects of this abuse. a lot of people never recover fully. the physical, emotional, mental, and whatever kind of trauma that exists, lingers. .
.
watching this r kelly documentary series stirred up so much anger. there are many ‚Äúr kellys‚Äù every where. they are in our homes, churches, schools, and every place we trust. most sexual abuse cases happen by a known perpetrator. .
.
this mess with r kelly lingered because we let people‚Äôs ‚Äògood side‚Äô stop us from seeing their true characters. we also constantly blame people for their experiences instead of fighting for and with them. r kelly has done and still does havoc. but, even more concerning is the predators we allow around us.
.
.
this is a fight! these molesters won‚Äôt back down if we stay passive. here are some things you can do:
1. look out for children and really anyone around you and don‚Äôt keep quiet if you notice anything odd
2. point out adults that sexualize children or teenagers. call them out! 
3. stop blaming victims of abuse for their abuse! children around you will hear it and suffer in silence
4. if you see something, say something
.
.
a lot of times, people who are abused end up abusing others. there is a whole psychological pathway that explains this. some people argue that‚Äôs how the monster r kelly came about. .
.
if you have been abused, get professional help. please, get help. if you know someone who has been, send them information on help.
the national sexual assault hotline is available 24/7: telephone: 800-656-hope (4673) online chat: online.rainn.org
‚†Ä‚†Ä
tag any organizations that can help and specify the country they serve. #wecanfightthis #wecanwin

text:
' surviving r. kelly' documentary on lifetime details sex abuse accussations.
.
.
for more than two decades, the r&b singer robert kelly, who performs as r. kelly, has faced accusations of sexual misconduct and abuse.

this week, a six-part documentary on lifetime is taking an expansive look at the allegations against mr. kelly. the series, ‚Äúsurviving r. kelly,‚Äù includes testimony from several women who accuse the singer of abuse, as well as commentary from mr. kelly‚Äôs critics, including the founder of the #metoo movement, tarana burke, and the singer john legend.

the six episodes, each an hour long, cover the long history of allegations against mr. kelly. they feature women who described being controlled or abused by him, often when they were teenagers, as well as associates and relatives of the singer.

mr. kelly has continuously denied the allegations against him.  the third and fourth episodes focused on mr. kelly‚Äôs 2008 child pornography trial and the sex tape at its center. the fifth and sixth episodes examine more recent allegations and follow parents who were trying to free their daughters from mr. kelly‚Äôs influence, ms. hampton said.

in the documentary, people who knew r. kelly claim that during the 1990s and 2000s, associates of the famous singer knew that he liked to prey on underage girls.

in 2002, a video that appeared to show mr. kelly having sex with a teenage girl and urinating in her mouth was sent to mr. derogatis at¬†the chicago sun-times, which reported that the footage was being investigated by the chicago police.

mr. legend and jamilah lemieux, have pointed people to organizations like¬†a long walk home, a chicago-based nonprofit working to end violence against girls and women; and¬†girls for gender equity, a nonprofit that has¬†created a guide¬†for viewers of the documentary, including those who are survivors of sexual assault.
by jacey fortin.
.
.

text:
ive realized lately that several women have been molested as children. i saw the #metoo movement and figured that my situation was not as important because i was never molested by any celebrity and it would not matter at this point because these things happened years ago. however, just the other night i was praying to god and he reminded me of these situations where i was molested and how certain seeds were planted in my heart from that moment up until adulthood. up until this day i still remember every touch, every kiss, and word spoken just like it was yesterday. i remember being told to keep quiet, that it should stay between me and them (i was just a little girl) and the anger in me was still there when the lord showed me those vivid visions. he was showing me that i still needed to be free from that, that i still had to forgive and not just bury it. some things when buried, feel like deliverance, but its just a big blanket covering a big problem. i am speaking out because 1) i am sure that someone reading this has been molested or violated in some way and probably feels like its something that you should just get over just because youre an adult, but these things plants seeds in your mind of worthlessness, bitterness, lust, you name it and it follows you into adulthood without you even realizing why you have these feelings. 
the enemy uses this strategy from childhood, to penetrate our souls and spirits with worthlessness and mistrust. now that the lord has opened my eyes, i see that the enemy was behind it the entire time i dont hate those who violated me, or anyone else who was not be there to protect me, simply because they did not know. i blame the enemy, he used people to violate me and other children and he's still doing it until this day. for those who have been violated, speak out, talk to god and be free from it. your violators may have told you to keep quiet but its time to speak out and be brave, they dont control you anymore. for those who have small children, protect them, cover them with the blood of jesus and rebuke the enemy and any device that he will try to use to harm them. its time that he take his hands off our children.

#metoo

text:
we all knew something wasn't right with this man the moment he forged aaliyah's age on that wedding certificate. i was only 13 and knew he had no business wanting to be with her!

pedophile: a person who is sexually attracted to children.

pervert: a person whose sexual behavior is regarded as abnormal and unacceptable.

predator: a person that ruthlessly exploits others.

psychopath: a person suffering from a chronic mental disorder with abnormal and violent social behavoirs.

the legal system failed when that sex tape wasn't enough to convict him of child pornography? she was a 14 year old baby.

and his antics continued right in front of society and the world at large, just tearing down, beating up, raping, emotionally bruising, manipulating, destroying our girls, our young ladies, our women, our future leaders and mothers of the next generation, and what do we do?

we support the music that confesses his sins, we listen despite it all and say "i'm not here to judge, i just like the music," and we go to his concerts because "he wasn't found guilty, so he must not be, right?" money buys a lot of things, including a verdict in some cases. even now that women are sharing their experiences with this monster and what do we do?

make his sales splurge...what the what?! you know what they say, "all publicity is good publicity" and we're just putting his name out there more and more, giving his musical voice to new audiences and right back to people who have forgotten about him so they can fall in love with the music all over again, smh!

the music is great, there's no denying it...from angelic to crude and overly sexual, but then again he was just sharing his dirty little secrets and telling his truths and we all just pretended it was all for entertainment. no wonder my daddy snatched up every tape and cd my sister and i owned of his...it's clear now why he didn't want us listening to this predator who uses his power and musical gifts and authority to lure young girls into his trance, mesmerizing the weak and vulnerable.

sorry m.j., but i'll never be able to listen to "you are not alone" the same again. #metoo #muterkelly #moneytalks

text:
i came across a final les mills jacket to donate and it made me pause to think. i am grateful to have left les mills last june 2018. for a community and ‚Äútr1be‚Äù to occur, there needs to be mutual trust, starting from the leadership setting the tone. valuable and trusting members and instructors deserve leadership who does their very best to stand up for women‚Äôs (and human) rights and does not empower multiple trainers to take advantage of women over time, or repeatedly mislead or find ways to take back their eventual and reluctant promise to send out an ‚Äúif you see something, say something‚Äù communication or provide changing and conflicting information in avoidance over time. a company should instead genuinely and proactively protect their members by offering a direct and confidential means to report negative behavior, and publicly notifying all of this system in place. no one is perfect, we all make mistakes or poor choices, but a company who comes across as supporting healthy lifestyle, equality, and women‚Äôs rights should have had this process in place years ago and not need to be pressured or repeatedly asked to protect and educate their valuable and trusting instructors and members over a long period of time.
it has been hard to step away from teaching, but i could never look a trusting potential instructor in the eye and confidently encourage them to take a training, knowing the ongoing behavior that was allowed or ‚Äúswept under the rug‚Äù by more than one trainer over long periods of time. 
i subbed a one-time class recently for a dear friend on holiday, and my heart soared seeing the passion, effort, and dedication members in the class gave- i sat in my car afterwards with a tear in my eye -pride seeing how much members overcome to attend classes and the second-by-second choice they make to give 100% towards their fitness and life goals. that is a sacred trust, and should never be taken lightly or given a false public persona, with an opposite and negative action behind the scenes and out of the spotlight. #lesmills #bemorehuman #metoo #reebok #lesmillstribe #lesmillsbodycombat #lesmillsbodypump

@lifetimetv @survivingrkelly this docuseries was very eye-opening. there are snippets of videos, photos, victims of the alleged accuser robert ‚Äúpied piper‚Äù kelly, victim‚Äô parents and so much more. 
_______________________________________________________
i see the many comments/opinions on multiple threads from those who support the #metoo #muterkelly movement & those who don‚Äôt. i know, at this point, people are tired of seeing posts about it, but honestly, get over it. this generation, social media, etc. has reached it‚Äôs level of tiredness for sweeping sh%^ under the rug. time out for that. #youtoo know people who have been mislead, abused, molested, and much more. i pray for the continuous encouragement for those who have been mistreated in the most monstrous ways to continue to raise their voices. for those who are going through it now, know you are not alone and step out on faith into the light with it, this is your season! one thing is for sure, they cannot all be lying (if this is your thought process). it was moving, emotional to watch & it will make you upset. there were somethings revealed i didn‚Äôt even know about. i was floored to know he stayed not too far from where we lived and worked too in atlanta. under our nose, under many people‚Äôs nose there is always something going on. thank god for those who speak up. men, especially our black men, we need you to protect us like never before. these women are alike not just from the pain they share but they are african-american women who have repeatedly experienced neglect! this is definitely not a general statement, we know there are black men taking care of our women but we need ya‚Äôll to continue to rise in areas of the community in the world where there is a gap. let‚Äôs keep it real... we have to protect our daughters, by all means necessary.

„Éª„Éª„Éª
take a moment to read my thoughts: i boycotted r. kelleys music in 2002 when i saw the video ~ i know it was him. clearly.  i wasn‚Äôt comfortable talking about it because the world i lived in .... everyone thought it was a joke, and they made me feel ike i was too earnest. i saw the bbc documentary, i read the buzz feed and new yorker articles ... as a #survivor and a black woman in the music industry, i just broke down sobbing when i saw the video. i sobbed, because it was a graphic illustration, that i lived in a world that didnt value people like me. and i had to learn to take care of myself in the face of a society and industry that doesn‚Äôt love me. i learned that i had to wear the crown of my ancestors and hold my own head up. and its been hard. but i do it because i believe in my mission ~ i don‚Äôt need to sing about the fight , my mission is to administer to the people in the fight. humanity makes me sad all the time ~ the things were going thru ... but also today, i‚Äôm hopeful, that we as a group are now #muterkelly ~ but, i wont be satisfied until every abused person knows, that ‚Äúeveryone of us is worthy‚Äù and when ever someone treats us as less, that is thier mistake, ... and while the wound is not our doing, it is our responsibility ~ we have to heal ourselves.  that healing can take on so much more momentum, when the world around us is healing too.... so i feel good today knowing that we as a collective are waking up even more, to the ways that the world / the music industry / the society / the culture ~ harm our women and girls.  and! i feel good today knowing that these growing pains are about growth. we are all! worthy and significant and we matter! because we exist!  may we keep waking up to that fact. it is a fact! everyone of us is #worthy #worthy #worthy #worthy #worthy #worthy #survivingrkelly #iamlight #muterkelly #survivingrkelly #rkelly #blackgirlsmatter #metoo

text:
after the release of the #survivingrkelly documentary, we all need to ask ourselves how we are supporting/advocating for/believing survivors of abuse and violence, particularly black women survivors.
‚Ä¢
as one of the eps of the documentary, #dreamhampton explained that black girls are often perceived as ‚Äúmore sexual at an early age. we perceive them to be older. and that is rooted ‚Äî there is no other way to say it, and it‚Äôs not hyperbole to say ‚Äî it‚Äôs absolutely rooted in this country‚Äôs history of slavery, which has gone on longer than it hasn‚Äôt.‚Äù
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
dream hampton was strategic in her role and reached out to stars in the music business about the show's core allegations: that r. kelly has spent decades pursuing sex with underage girls, maintaining abusive relationships with women and videotaping sexual activities without their consent. and that many people were/ are still complicit in allowing this abuse to continue.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
not only do we want to applaud the work of the producers like dream hampton, but most importantly we want to recognize the bravery of the survivors who have given their testimony knowing that they will be faced with doubt, shame, or worse. they are heroes and we believe them.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
please swipe to read the #metoomvmt tips for viewing the documentary, also shared by another #dailyherstory social justice warrior and creator of #metoo, @taranajaneen (who also appears in the documentary).
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
and plz hold yourself and others accountable - unfollow r. kelly, don‚Äôt stream his music, call out those who collaborate with him. we should be doing the same for all perpetrators of violence against women and/or sexual assault of minors (johnny depp, woody allen, cristiano ronaldo, and too many more successful men who claim such allegations ‚Äúruin their careers‚Äù) and listening to the accounts of their survivors.

text:
silenced by mersi stone @korijeanolsen and @kelsiolsen to watch the full video go to: https://youtu.be/qtucsfk3b-a
.
.
did you know that there are over 12.7 million people that are physically abused, raped, or stalked by their partners every year? ¬†that is the population of new york and los angeles combined. that is 24 people every minute. shockingly, it is most likely someone that you know..
.
.
i met one of the amazing members of the duo mersi stone, kori jean olsen, earlier this year and her story is one that i will not soon forget. this song was written by she and her sister, kelsi, from the depths of kori jean's struggle. watching this video had me in tears. many of the words that these victims held up throughout the video has been defining their life for years and will haunt them for years to come. these victims are real, they walk amongst us every single day. the problem is that they do so in silence. i want all of you to know, there is help. there is freedom. i recognize the risk of speaking out, but i also recognize the utter agony if you do not. ¬†please know that there are people that can help you. ¬†i have referenced them below. if you know of someone who is experiencing this kind of abuse, please report the incident. you have to realize that when you are a victim of a relationship like this, you are literally threatened, beaten, demoralized, discredited, humiliated, shamed.....and ultimately silenced. there are so many who have lost their voice, we can help them find it. pay attention. if it sounds odd, looks "not right" follow your gut, it probably isn't..
.
.
here are five signs of possible abuse: change in habits, constantly on edge, any physical bruising or wounds, lack of communication or continual changing of plans, faking emotions or excusing the emotion of themselves or significant other.
i know that bringing up this type of an allegation is not easy at all and it runs the risk of the victim isolating themselves from you and loved ones further. i would recommend speaking with one of the members of any of the hotlines listed in the comments section below.. continued in comments..

more than 100,000 women marched in major cities across the uk to mark the centenary of the women‚Äôs vote, meghan markle became the first woman of colour to marry into the royal family, ireland voted to overturn its abortion laws, and even three-year-old princess charlotte made history when she was able to retain her succession to the throne despite the birth of a younger male sibling. and lest we forget jodie whittaker‚Äôs debut as the first female doctor who.

this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

joshua green

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
in #bangkok, right now, this young #saudi woman is in the fight of her life. rahaf mohammed fled her family in ksa (saudi arabia) via #kuwait because she renounced her #islamic faith and did not want to enter into an arranged marriage.
-
on her arrival in #thailand - through which she was only passing on her way to #australia - her passport and valid visa was snatched and she was forcibly moved to an airport hotel. this was done by the thai authorities with the full knowledge and coercion of the saudi government.
-
the plan was to put rahaf on a plane back to kuwait, to her family, where she faces certain death. apostasy is a capital crime in #ksa.
-
as i write this, rahaf remains in the bangkok hotel. the plane that was to take her back left without her. the world is snapping to agonized attention.
-
forget the #goldenglobes. forget the #nfl. forget the #womensmarch (actually *fuck* the women's march). forget #metoo. this is the story of the moment. rahaf's plight is the plight of countless women who are suffering under the yoke of a fanatical state, whose regard for women is less than animals.
-
#saverahaf #deanfromaustralia #feminism #women #freedom #unhcr

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i‚Äôve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i‚Äôm about to go back, knowing what i know, and we‚Äôre about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump‚Äôs election, trumpeted the return of their ‚Äúpopulist hero‚Äù on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication‚Äôs announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

tweet_full:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to cou documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the cou documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagate‚Ñ¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

trump plays along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still - the republicans willingly piggybacked this before the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

the me too movement (or #metoo movement), with many local and international alternative names, is a movement against sexual harassment and sexual assault.[1][2][3] #metoo spread virally in october 2017 as a hashtag on social media in an attempt to demonstrate the widespread prevalence of sexual assault and harassment, especially in the workplace.[4][5][6] it followed soon after the sexual abuse allegations against harvey weinstein.[7][8] tarana burke, an american social activist and community organizer, began using the phrase "me too" as early as 2006, and the phrase was later popularized by american actress alyssa milano, on twitter in 2017. milano encouraged victims of sexual harassment to tweet about it and "give people a sense of the magnitude of the problem".[9][10] this was met with success that included but was not limited to high-profile posts from several american celebrities, including gwyneth paltrow,[11] ashley judd,[12] jennifer lawrence,[13] and uma thurman.[14]

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text_retweet:
as i prepare to head back to my 9-5 as a child advocate, i am compelled to share this message this morning. as parents we can become too comfortable and lax with our children because we're distracted & focused on making a living/better life for our children.  every other tuesday i sit in a room in little ol houston county ga and i hear all of the current sex abuse cases in our county.  this is the most depressing day for me.  so depressing in fact, that once the meeting is over i have to leave and decompress, collect myself, cry, pray, be angry, and cry some more.  yes, in this small county our children are being sexually abused at alarming rates. and 95% of the victims are victimized by people the family "knows." mom's boyfriend, cousins, uncles, and even grandparents.  outside of the boyfriends these are people you automatically trust to protect your child.  it's not just our girls, it's our boys too. it's time we start having some real honest conversations in our community!!! #iamforthechild
*
*
reposted from @theconsciouskid -  practical tips from mom and pediatrician, dr. tobi adeyeye amosun, on the likely scenarios of who/where/when child sexual abuse occurs, how to talk to your kids about it, and how to make your kids feel safe.
.
.
she starts by saying: "without going into graphic details, i probably get about 1-2 kids a month in my office who have been sexually abused or molested. i will address each of the things that i mentioned above in light of the most common scenarios i‚Äôve seen." swipe left for her full text. full article also linked in our stories. let us know your thoughts on this. 
#sexualabuse #parenting #motherhood #fatherhood #consent #raisingkids #sexualassault #survivingrkelly #metoo #consciousparenting #knowledgeispower #childhoodsexualabuse #sleepovers #pediatrician
